<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence by  Kent County Council into the Education Committee’s Inquiry into the Government’s Proposals with regards to Residential Children’s Homes</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">RCH0008</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">submitted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">by Kent County Council </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent County Council (KCC) welcomes the opportunity to submit its evidence to the Education Committee, on its inquiry into the Government’s reform to the regulation governing residential children’s homes.  KCC’s evidence is based on many years’ experience of dealing with the challenges related to the high number of out of area placements into some of the most deprived areas in the county.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission addresses the two principal points that the Committee posed, namely that: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(a) Whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the proposed reforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are appropriate, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(b) Whether there are a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dditional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">easures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that should be considered. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In doing so, we have identified the following areas where we believe additional measures are warranted:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Notification obligations of children’s homes’ and placing authorities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Adequacy of the existing sufficiency regulations that place a duty on local authorities to develop local resources for looked after children</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Emergency placements</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Corporate parent responsibilities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Risk assessment</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Planning regulations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of other key agencies</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is home to 322,813</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children and young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">according to the 2011 Census. A number of the characteristics of the county mirror the south east’s relative material comfort compared to other parts of the country. Even so, it contains some areas of deprivation which rank along the most deprived in England.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC currently supports </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1,821</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at the end </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">August</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> looked after children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the rate of looked after children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at 5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> per 10,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (excluding unaccompanied asylum seeking children)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">below</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the national average (59.0)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the actual number of looked after children in the KCC area are far greater than the above figure. There is an additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1,212</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at the end </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">August</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> other local authority out of area (OOA) looked after children placements into Kent. The OOA placements present a significant safeguarding management challenge for Children’s Social Services, Police, Schools and Health Services in the Kent area. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent also has the highest number (244) of children’s homes places available (DfE Children’s Home’s Data Pack, 2013) in the country. The number of KCC children placed in the 71 privately registered children’s homes in Kent is 34 (14%), as at August 2013.  Very few KCC children are placed in Thanet children’s homes. Furthermore, there are 3 children’s homes in one of the two foremost wards in Margate. None of the KCC’s 34 children are placed in the 3 children’s homes in Cliftonville West, Margate (as at the end of August 2013). This gives ample evidence that Kent’s children’s homes are serving both the market and financial needs of other authorities that have not adequately responded to children’s needs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Foster Service in Kent has made considerable progress with 1,224 (as at the end of August 2013) placed with foster parents.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The existence of the Port of Dover and other factors has led to Kent bearing the highest number of Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children (UASC) in England. The Children’s Social Care Team currently supports 635 children (203</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> looked after children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as at the end of August 2013).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(A) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appropriateness of the proposed reforms </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Focusing on the two ends of the continuum of support - prevention and protection measures should provide the necessary safeguarding for children</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC agrees with the policy intention to strengthen residential children’s homes’ prevention and responsive safeguarding systems so that children are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">receiving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the most effective protection. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We strongly believe that the proposed reforms based on the principle of shared responsibilities between the placing authority, registered provider and responsible person are timely. In our view, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> measures need to be put into practice as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> necessary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ingredient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of effective partnership working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such that placement decisions take proper account of local community safety factors in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensuring the protection of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safeguard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> vulnerable children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Notification</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">requirements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC is supportive of the specific proposals which place a duty on registered homes to notify the local authority when children move in as OOA placements from other local authority areas and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> when they subsequently leave the home. However, we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> misgivings that the requirements would fail to achieve the intended outcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not backed by some kind of sanction to address persistent failure to provide timely notification to the receiving authority. We argue further that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">corporate responsibility role of placing authorities should not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">diminish simply because they have made OOA placements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.     </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Risk assessment</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are encouraged that regulations will stipulate that a joint risk assessment between the police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the local authority and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NHS should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">carried out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as part of the registration requirement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We urge that   such risk assessments ought to be carried out in conjunction with the host authority. We also think it is important and appropriate that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> information </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shared with key agencies in a timely manner.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Out of area placement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our view, it is right that the rules are strengthened so that the receiving local authority senior official approves OOA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">placements,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> considerable distance from a child’s home. All the same</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we are not convinced that there is sufficient clarity about th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> steps that the DfE propose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to ensure compliance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with the requirement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that placements should be within 20 miles for the majority of children. As noted above, there are 1,2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> OOA placements in Kent, with a high proportion of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> children placed over 80 miles from their homes. We have to ask whether the children’s best interest are always served</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in some of the cases.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Safe location</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC is delighted that from January 2014, HMCI will only allow new homes to open in safe areas, managed by competent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">registered providers and responsible persons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The county council has strong reservations that safe location will remain as a concept until OOA placement into areas of high levels of deprivation is effectively tack</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> otherwise this increases the risk of exploitation, harm or abuse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of vulnerable children</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to see more done in this regard and call for a change in the planning legislation so that bail hostels and other provisions of that kind should not be opened within 5 miles radius of a children’s home.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">KCC also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">welcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e fact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re is to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national minimum standards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in respect of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the recruitment, training and supervision of staff that work in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">residential care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> settings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(B) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Additional measures needed </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We hold the view that it is important to strike the right balance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reliance on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">guidance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">focus on actual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">practi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. Ultimately, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> key question</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> is whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">proposals will result in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a change in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> behaviour </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> authorities and providers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Notification obligations of children’s homes’ and placing authorities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These reforms </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should help to strengthen the focus on safeguarding; however, we believe it is vital for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further consideration to be given to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">adequacy of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sufficien</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cy requirements placed on local authorities with regard to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> provision of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children’s homes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in local authority areas. Since April 2011, local authorities have been required to plan for and, develop local resources for looked after children. The historic pattern of placing children far away from home, and the fact that some authorities have no local resources, attests to the fact that authorities in general have some way to go before it could be said that the sufficiency duty placed on local authorities is having the right impact. We call on the government to urge smaller local authorities to collaborate to commission residential placements for children along the lines of the successful West London councils’ consortium.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We consider that in order for the notification system to have the required effect, it will be important for the placing authority to  effectively communicate  with the receiving authority. Notification by itself is not enough, there needs to be sound dialogue and improved communication. We believe effective notification process will help receiving authorities to have a view as to the emerging issues and trends which may require early attention in order to minimise any potential adverse incidents.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Emergency placements</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We wish to draw attention to the fact that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on balance, the proposed reforms provide adequate platform for planned placements. However, we do not think that the proposed amendments can adequately deal with placements made in emergency circumstances. We therefore believe that further thoughts should be given to this point and crucially, test whether these changes can satisfactorily deal with placements made under emergency situations given the greater emphasis that is placed on r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isk assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Corporate Parent responsibilities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst we believe that the proposed amendments to the regulations should lead to improvements in how residential homes discharge their prevention and protective duties, we contend that these reforms should not result in the dilution of local authority corporate parent responsibilities.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Risk assessment</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our view the changes to be introduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> annual risk assessments will enable local areas to build a whole system profile of the geographical location where children’s residential care homes are situated.  This will be enhanced if sufficient attention is paid to the broader external environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> factors, including matters such as anti- social behaviour profile in relation to the immediate vicinity of children’s homes. Also, it is essential that individuals, whose role required that they undertake </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk assessments should be trained, attain the necessary skills and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their competency confirmed through a formal assessment process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Amendment of section 17 of the Crime and Disorder Act 1998, to place statutory requirement on a Placing Authority to consider the crime and disorder implications of its actions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the area they intend to place children out of area will further improve the reforms. We observe that currently, the statutory duty falls only on the Receiving Authority.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Planning regulations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Also, due consideration should be given to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">current planning regulations in relation to children’s homes to ensure that children’s homes are not opened in areas that present a high risk to the children being placed, including checks on number of registered sex offenders in the area, trafficking and gang activity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The point about planning regulations presents a further complication in two-tier local government area where the social care authority and the planning authority are not the same. We reiterate the point about a change in the planning legislation made earlier in paragraph 3.6 above.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe that great transparency over ownership of children’s homes is required. It is often difficult, in delivery care to children under pressing circumstances, to ascertain who owns the home through tracking the record. This situation is compounded, where the financial management of some private equity firm of the home or company that has a poor track record of quality of service operates in a different place under a different name. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of other key agencies</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The role of other agencies such as the Prison Service in respect of prison releases should be carefully considered, in particular, with reference to the implementation of prison service dispersal policy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(C) Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Kent is host to a large number of children’s residential care homes with 244 placement capacity and a host to 1,212 out of area placements into the county. There are over 70 privately registered children’s homes in Kent. The reform proposals have clear financial implications for Kent County Council, as additional resources (staff resource and time) will have to be made available in order to help manage the increased activities that these proposals will generate, including:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">notification administration resources</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">input to the Ofsted pre-registration process</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authorisation of Regulations 33 Visitors to all homes in the area</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signing off pathway plans for voluntary accommodated 16-17 year old young people who leave care</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">workforce training on the new framework</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The budget pressures will not fall on Kent County Council alone. Indeed, we forecast that there will be also be a direct impact on Police, schools and health services in the county.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are pleased that the Education Select Committee is conducting inquiry into the Government’s proposals with regard to residential children’s homes. Kent County Council will be willing to provide further information on any aspects in our submission should the Committee wish to receive any additional material.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>